This paper discusses the structure and centralization of the Internet, which falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). It also discusses the potential for censorship and filtering, which falls under the category of security and privacy (cs.CR). The paper also touches on the business decisions that contribute to centralization, which falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). Additionally, the paper discusses the impact on users in different countries, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI) and cybercrime and cybersecurity (cs.CY).
